Music 78, otherwise known as the History of Jazz music, is one of the most popular classes taken at the University of California Irvine. Whether students are taking it to fulfill a last general education requirement or taking it out of their own interest, you can count on the lecture hall being filled every class. Kei Akagi, the Chancellor Professor of Music at UCI has been teaching the class now for several years. Akagi is an accomplished jazz pianist and composer. He has recorded several albums and worked with other famous musicians such as Stanley Turrentine, Flora Plurim, and Miles Davis. In Music 78, Akagi teaches students how jazz came to be, the history surrounding the music, how jazz music is formatted, and its significance to music today. Much of the class involves listening to recordings and even live performances by Akagi and other faculty members.
            	On the first day of Music 78 this year, Akagi introduced the class website, which he states he has been using for several years now. The course website gives students access to class materials such as the syllabus, schedule, and recordings of jazz music. However, the website looks very outdated. Akagi has even called the website sad to some regard. There are no images, no stylized elements, and everything is in black and white. We, The Ampersands, have offered to redesign the course website for Professor Akagi. We would like to create an appealing and user-friendly website for Music 78. Our goal is to have the redesign become the new course website for years to come.

WHY ARE WE DOING THIS      	
            	The Ampersands would like to redesign the course website because we feel that there will be a great benefit to improving the website for one of the most popular classes at UCI. The current website is not the most appealing or user-friendly. It hasnt been updated for years, there are no images, stylized elements, and some of the text is hard to read. With a class size of 205 students, its important that the course website be as user-friendly as possible.
WHY WERE THE PEOPLE TO DO IT
            	We believe were the group of people to do it because we have the skills needed to implement a website. We have experience using HTML, CSS, different APIs, libraries, web development and conducting user studies. We are familiar with how course websites are at UCI and what students expect while using one. We are passionate about improving user experience. One of our members is a Studio Art major, and another one of our members has played jazz music before. We are a group of individuals whom have the technical skills and interests to build this new website.

The current website is not the most appealing or user-friendly. It hasnt been updated for years. There are no images, stylized elements, and much of the text is difficult to read. It can be described as plain, dull, and even the professor has gone on to describe it as sad. We feel that the website doesnt give a good impression about the class and what it has to offer. For example, a student who is looking at course websites of different classes to decide what to take may look at the Music 78 course website and based on how the website currently looks, they may assume the class is boring and pass on taking it. There are also evident problems for students who actually take the class. Much of the text presented on the screen is all the same font and same size. This makes it hard for a student to find specific information. When everything looks the same, nothing stands out. The class is one of the most popular classes taken at UCI. There is almost always a waitlist at the beginning of each quarter it is taught. We feel this class deserves a better course website, one that is fresh, updated, appealing, and user-friendly. Our goal is to have students more engaged with the class and the subject material just from using the website. The professor is also a very accomplished jazz musician who has worked with one of the most famous jazz musicians ever, Miles Davis. It would be a great opportunity to add a section that highlights the accomplishments of the professor and gives a little information about him into the website as well. We feel we have the opportunity to lend our technical skills to help Professor Akagi with his website and in a sense, give back to our school. The Ampersands will redesign his website, transforming it into a creative, functional, and user-friendly experience for future students. We have the opportunity to not only use our skills but improve them as well throughout this whole process. This can lead to more opportunities to redesign other class websites in the Arts Department or other departments.

It is doable in 8 weeks if we properly manage our time between the different parts we have in mind. Getting interviews from students and then coming up with mockups of a better website shouldnt need too much time. All that is left after that is to do some mockups and then actually creating the new website. A redesigned school website would allow the professor to provide more engaging materials and information to the students more efficiently. It might also make it that much more interesting to students the history of jazz if the website was updated and trendy versus an outdated one that is confusing and just plain old-looking.

The proposed redesigning of the school website for the jazz class must be overall a better and improved design so that it is easier for students/professors to navigate through the materials. Students, teachers, and other potential interested parties should find the new website easy to use while still being able to interact with rich contents. The website also need be trendy, colorful, and attractive so as not to feel outdated while still providing necessary information with regards to the history of jazz. The professor who will be the main person in charge of the website after it is done should be able to freely make changes easily as he see fit to the new website if he choose to do so. Ultimately the new website should be an extended tool that the professor can use to more effectively expose all his students to the wonderful materials out there that is the history of jazz.  In regards to technical specification, the new website should be to do everything the previous one can do. It should not require any new hardware or software and should be able to just effectively take over the old previous website.

The goal of this project is to have it completed and done in about 8 weeks timed. We have four final deliverable products in mind which consist of the documentation requirements, interviews data/results, mockups of what the website would look like, and the actual website itself. This means we have roughly about 2 weeks for each part if we decide to split the time remaining evenly between the four parts.  Even less if we take account of other courses workload this quarter since this isnt the only class we have to worry about. If it was just this class alone for this quarter, 8 weeks would give us plenty of time to work around each parts and probably extra time to polish everything too. Hopefully even with other classes to worry about, we will be able to manage our time well and not have to cut any corners to do so. We also expect the newly redesigned class website to last a fairly long time since it will be trendy and allow the professor to freely update contents to the website. It should take over the old and outdated current website that the professor is still using and become the next long stable website for that class.

There are many risks involved while attempting this project. The first is us underestimating the actual time required this whole project. We only assumed that it is doable within the time frame with regards to the skills and workload required for this redesign. It might turn out that we actually dont have the required skills or knowledge to create a website or that the amount of work required is too overwhelming. Another major risk is the supposedly easy to use interface for the students and most importantly the professor. If the professor finds it really hard to add or edit content onto the website, everything else will just follow suit and flop. Finally, if the finished website does not offer or provide a more refreshing updated user experiences which was the whole purpose of the redesign in the first place, it would mean all our work and time spent on this project was all for nothing. Of course, the big and foremost school risk is that we are doing this project for an academic grade. If we do a half-assed job or ended up with an unfinished project in the end, we will most likely receive a failing grade which would be devastating to us.

	- What Else is Out There
	The main competitors of Professor Akagis website includes other jazz class websites or other class websites of popular classes in the same General Education category. These classes all attract the same demographic of student (either music majors or students who need a class like this to fulfill their GE requirements). The History of Jazz therefore website must not only teach students, but also encourage students to take the class over other possible choices.
The largest competitors in the same General Education category at UCI include ED124: Multicultural Education K-12 (https://eee.uci.edu/13w/12200), AFAM 40B: Racial Theories in Context (https://eee.uci.edu/13w/20240), WOMN ST 50B: Gender and Power (https://eee.uci.edu/13w/32530), SOCIOL 63: Race and Ethnicity (https://eee.uci.edu/13w/69300).
For other music course websites, competitors include The History of Jazz at the University of Virginia (http://people.virginia.edu/~skd9r/MUSI212_new/) and UCI courses such as Interactive Arts Programming (http://www.healthyboys.com/Music152/), Musicianship (http://music.arts.uci.edu/mdessen/current/mus15A/), Music Theory II (https://eee.uci.edu/13w/04050/), and J.S. Bach (https://eee.uci.edu/13w/04085).
	-Is There A Market For It
	There is indeed a market for for this project, as Professor Akagi personally advertised during one of the lectures that he was looking for help in remaking the website for his History of Jazz course. With this website in particular, the fact that it is a recurring course taught by Akagi, there is even more incentive to have the website updated, since it is reused each time the course is offered. With the amount of traffic course websites receive in general from university students checking them almost daily, there will always be a market for a more user-friendly and more up-to-date website.
